# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: monogame
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The principal designers of the C# programming language were Anders Hejlsberg, Scott Wiltamuth, and Peter Golde from Microsoft.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] It was first widely distributed in July 2000 and was later approved as an international standard by Ecma (ECMA-334) in 2002 and ISO/IEC (ISO/IEC 23270 and 20619) in 2003.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft introduced C# along with .NET Framework and Microsoft Visual Studio, both of which are, technically speaking, closed-source.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] At the time, Microsoft had no open-source products.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Four years later, in 2004, a free and open-source project called Mono began, providing a cross-platform compiler and runtime environment for the C# programming language.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] A decade later, Microsoft released Visual Studio Code (code editor), Roslyn (compiler), and the unified .NET platform (software framework), all of which support C# and are free, open-source, and cross-platform.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Mono also joined Microsoft, but was not merged into .NET.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] As of November 2025, the most recent stable version of the language is C# 14.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] During the development of the .NET Framework, the class libraries were originally written using a managed code compiler system named *Simple Managed C* (SMC).
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] In January 1999, Anders Hejlsberg formed a team to build a new language at the time called COOL, which stood for "C-like Object Oriented Language".
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft had considered keeping the name "COOL(C-like Object Oriented Language)" as the final name of the language, but chose not to do so for trademark reasons.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] By the time the .NET project was publicly announced at the July 2000 Professional Developers Conference, the language had been renamed C#, and the class libraries and ASP.NET runtime were ported to C#.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Hejlsberg was C#'s principal designer and lead architect at Microsoft, and had been previously involved with the design of Turbo Pascal, Embarcadero Delphi (formerly CodeGear Delphi, Inprise Delphi and Borland Delphi), and Visual J++.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] In interviews and technical papers, he has stated that flaws in most major programming languages (e.g.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] C++, Java, Delphi, and Smalltalk) drove the fundamentals of the Common Language Runtime (CLR), which, in turn, drove the design of the C# language.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] In July 2000, Hejlsberg said that C# is "not a Java clone" and is "much closer to C++" in its design.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Since the release of C# 2.0 in November 2005, the C# and Java languages have evolved on increasingly divergent trajectories, becoming two quite different languages.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] One of the first major departures came with the addition of generics to both languages, with vastly different implementations.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] C# uses reification to provide "first-class" generic objects that can be used like any other class, with code generation performed at class-load time.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has also added several major features to accommodate functional-style programming, culminating in the LINQ extensions released with C# 3.0 and its supporting framework of lambda expressions, extension methods, and anonymous types.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] These features enable C# programmers to use functional programming techniques, such as closures, when it is advantageous to their application.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] C# used to have a mascot called Andy (named after Anders Hejlsberg).
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] C# was originally submitted to the ISO/IEC JTC 1 subcommittee SC 22 for review, under ISO/IEC 23270:2003, was withdrawn and was then approved under ISO/IEC 23270:2006.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The 23270:2006 is withdrawn under 23270:2018 and approved with this version.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft first used the name C# in 1988 for a variant of the C language designed for incremental compilation.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] That project was not completed, and the name was later reused.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The name "C sharp" was inspired by the musical notation whereby a sharp symbol indicates that the written note should be made a semitone higher in pitch.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] This is similar to the language name of C++, where "++" indicates that a variable should be incremented by 1 after being evaluated.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The sharp symbol also resembles a ligature of four "+" symbols (in a two-by-two grid), further implying that the language is an increment of C++.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Due to technical limits of display (standard fonts, browsers, etc.), and most keyboard layouts lacking a sharp symbol (U+266F ♯ MUSIC SHARP SIGN (&sharp;)), the number sign (U+0023 # NUMBER SIGN (&num;)) was chosen to approximate the sharp symbol in the written name of the programming language.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] This convention is reflected in the ECMA-334 C# Language Specification.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The "sharp" suffix has been used by a number of other Microsoft .NET compatible/compliant languages that are variants of existing languages, including J# (a .NET language also designed by Microsoft that is derived from Java 1.1), A# (from Ada), and the functional programming language F#.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The original implementation of Eiffel for .NET was called Eiffel#, a name retired since the full Eiffel language is now supported.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The suffix has also been used for libraries, such as Gtk# (a .NET wrapper for GTK and other GNOME libraries) and Cocoa# (a wrapper for Cocoa).
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Development of the text for standards (beginning with C# 6) is done on GitHub.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] C# 7 was submitted to Ecma and approved in December 2023.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] As of January 2024, the standard for C# 8 is currently under development, referencing the approved language proposals.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] By design, C# is the programming language that most directly reflects the underlying Common Language Infrastructure (CLI).
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Most of its intrinsic types correspond to value-types implemented by the CLI framework.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] However, the language specification does not state the code generation requirements of the compiler: that is, it does not state that a C# compiler must target a Common Language Runtime (CLR), or generate Common Intermediate Language (CIL), or generate any other specific format.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Some C# compilers can also generate machine code like traditional compilers of Objective-C, C, C++, Assembly and Fortran.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] C# supports strongly, implicitly typed variable declarations with the keyword `var`, and implicitly typed arrays with the keyword `new[]` followed by a collection initializer.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Due to their special handling of the equality operator and their immutability, strings will nevertheless behave as if they were values, for all practical purposes.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The programmer can even use them as case labels.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Where necessary, value types will be boxed automatically.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] C# supports a strict Boolean data type, `bool`.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Statements that take conditions, such as `while` and `if`, require an expression of a type that evaluates to the `true` boolean value.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] While C++ also has a Boolean type, it can be freely converted to and from integers, and expressions such as `if (a)` require only that `a` is convertible to bool, allowing `a` to be an int, or a pointer.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] C# disallows this "integer meaning true or false" approach, on the grounds that forcing programmers to use expressions that return exactly `bool` can prevent certain types of programming mistakes such as `if (a = b)` (use of assignment `=` instead of equality `==`).
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The only implicit conversions by default are those that are considered safe, such as widening of integers.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] This is enforced at compile-time, during Just-in-time compilation, and, in some cases, at runtime.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] No implicit conversions occur between Booleans and integers, nor between enumeration members and integers (except for literal 0, which can be implicitly converted to any enumerated type).
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Any user-defined conversion must be explicitly marked as explicit or implicit, unlike C++ copy constructors and conversion operators, which are both implicit by default.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has explicit support for covariance and contravariance in generic types, unlike C++ which has some degree of support for contravariance simply through the semantics of return types on virtual methods.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Enumeration members are placed in their own scope.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The C# language does not allow for global variables or functions.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] All methods and members must be declared within classes.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Static members of public classes can substitute for global variables and functions.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Local variables cannot shadow variables of the enclosing block, unlike C and C++, but may shadow type-level names.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] A *method* in C# is a member of a class that can be invoked as a function, rather than the mere value-holding capability of a *field*, i.e., class or instance variable.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Different from most other languages, call-by-reference parameters have to be marked both at the function definition and at the calling site, and the programmer can choose between `ref` and `out`, the latter allowing handing over an uninitialized variable which will have a definite value on return.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Additionally, the programmer can specify a variable-sized argument list by applying the `params` keyword to the last parameter.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Certain specific kinds of methods, such as those that simply get or set a field's value by returning or assigning it, do not require an explicitly stated full signature, but in the general case, the definition of a class includes the full signature declaration of its methods.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Like C++, and unlike Java, C# programmers must use the scope modifier keyword `virtual` to allow methods to be overridden by subclasses.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike C++, the programmer must explicitly specify the keyword `override` when doing so.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] This is supposed to avoid confusion between overriding and newly overloading a function, i.e., hiding the former implementation.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] To do the latter, the programmer has to specify the `new` keyword.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The keyword `sealed` can be used to disallow further overrides for individual methods or whole classes.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The type `dynamic` allows for run-time method binding, allowing for JavaScript-like method calls and run-time object composition.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has support for strongly-typed function pointers via the keyword `delegate`.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Like the Qt framework's pseudo-C++ *signal* and *slot*, C# has semantics specifically surrounding publish-subscribe style events, though C# uses delegates to do so.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike fields, `event` variables can be part of an interface, because they technically consist of two default functions to add and remove to-be-called delegates.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] C# offers Java-like `synchronized` method calls, via the attribute `[MethodImpl(MethodImplOptions.Synchronized)]`, and has support for mutually-exclusive locks via the keyword `lock`.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The properties can be simple accessor functions with a backing field, or implement arbitrary getter and setter functions.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] A property is read-only if there's no setter.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Like with fields, there can be class and instance properties.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The underlying methods can be `virtual` or `abstract` like any other method.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Since C# 3.0 the syntactic sugar of auto-implemented properties is available, where the accessor (getter) and mutator (setter) encapsulate operations on a single field of a class.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] A C# `namespace` provides the same level of code isolation as a Java `package` or a C++ `namespace`, with rules and features very similar to a `package`.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Namespaces can be imported with the "using" syntax.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] In C#, memory address pointers can only be used within blocks specifically marked as *unsafe*, and programs with unsafe code need appropriate permissions to run.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Most object access is done through safe object references, which always either point to a "live" object or have the well-defined null value; it is impossible to obtain a reference to a "dead" object (one that has been garbage collected), or to an arbitrary block of memory.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] An unsafe pointer can point to an instance of an unmanaged value type that does not contain any references to objects subject to garbage collections such as class instances, arrays or strings.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Code that is not marked as unsafe can still store and manipulate pointers through the `System.IntPtr` type, but it cannot dereference them.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Managed memory cannot be explicitly freed; instead, it is automatically garbage collected.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Garbage collection addresses the problem of memory leaks by freeing the programmer of responsibility for releasing memory that is no longer needed in most cases.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Code that retains references to objects longer than is required can still experience higher memory usage than necessary, however once the final reference to an object is released the memory is available for garbage collection.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] A range of standard exceptions are available to programmers.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Methods in standard libraries regularly throw system exceptions in some circumstances and the range of exceptions thrown is normally documented.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Custom exception classes can be defined for classes allowing handling to be put in place for particular circumstances as needed.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] This is usually called a "try-catch" code block, because of the "try" and "catch" functions being used and accessible on all C# versions.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] If inspecting the error details is not required, the `(Exception ex)` parameter can be omitted as well.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Also, there can be several "catch" parts handling different kinds of exceptions.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Checked exceptions are not present in C# (in contrast to Java).
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] This has been a conscious decision based on the issues of scalability and version management.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike C++, C# does not support multiple inheritance, although a class can implement any number of "interfaces" (fully abstract classes).
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] This was a design decision by the language's lead architect to avoid complications and to simplify architectural requirements throughout CLI.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] When implementing multiple interfaces that contain a method with the same name and taking parameters of the same types in the same order, i.e., the same signature, similar to Java, C# allows both a single method to cover all interfaces and, if necessary, specific methods for each interface.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] C# also offers function overloading (a.k.a. ad-hoc-polymorphism), i.e., methods with the same name, but distinguishable signatures.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike Java, C# additionally supports operator overloading.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Since version 2.0, C# offers parametric polymorphism, i.e., classes with arbitrary or constrained type parameters, e.g., `List<T>`, a variable-sized array which only can contain elements of type `T`.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] There are certain kinds of constraints the programmer can specify for the type parameters: Has to be type X (or one derived from it), has to implement a certain interface, has to be a reference type, has to be a value type, has to implement a public parameterless constructor.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Most of them can be combined, and any number of interfaces can be specified.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has the ability to utilize LINQ through the .NET Framework.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] A developer can query a variety of data sources, provided the `IEnumerable<T>` interface is implemented on the object.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] This includes XML documents, an ADO.NET dataset, and SQL databases.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Using LINQ in C# brings advantages like IntelliSense support, strong filtering capabilities, type safety with compile error checking ability, and consistency for querying data over a variety of sources.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] There are several different language structures that can be utilized with C# and LINQ and they are query expressions, lambda expressions, anonymous types, implicitly typed variables, extension methods, and object initializers.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] LINQ has two syntaxes: query syntax and method syntax.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] However, the compiler always converts the query syntax to method syntax at compile time.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] This unified type system is called Common Type System (CTS).
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] A unified type system implies that all types, including primitives such as integers, are subclasses of the `System.Object` class.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] For example, every type inherits a `ToString()` method.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Instances of value types neither have referential identity nor referential comparison semantics.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Equality and inequality comparisons for value types compare the actual data values within the instances, unless the corresponding operators are overloaded.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Value types are derived from `System.ValueType`, always have a default value, and can always be created and copied.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Other examples are `enum` (enumerations) and `struct` (user defined structures).
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] In contrast, reference types have the notion of referential identity, meaning that each instance of a reference type is inherently distinct from every other instance, even if the data within both instances is the same.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] This is reflected in default equality and inequality comparisons for reference types, which test for referential rather than structural equality, unless the corresponding operators are overloaded (such as the case for `System.String`).
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Some operations are not always possible, such as creating an instance of a reference type, copying an existing instance, or performing a value comparison on two existing instances.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Nevertheless, specific reference types can provide such services by exposing a public constructor or implementing a corresponding interface (such as `ICloneable` or `IComparable`).
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Examples of reference types are `object` (the ultimate base class for all other C# classes), `System.String` (a string of Unicode characters), and `System.Array` (a base class for all C# arrays).
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Both type categories are extensible with user-defined types.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The C# specification details a minimum set of types and class libraries that the compiler expects to have available.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] In practice, C# is most often used with some implementation of the Common Language Infrastructure (CLI), which is standardized as ECMA-335 *Common Language Infrastructure (CLI)*.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] In addition to the standard CLI specifications, there are many commercial and community class libraries that build on top of the .NET framework libraries to provide additional functionality.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] C# can make calls to any library included in the List of .NET libraries and frameworks.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The line above imports all types in the `System` namespace.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] For example, the `Console` class used later in the source code is defined in the `System` namespace, meaning it can be used without supplying the full name of the type (which includes the namespace).
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] This line is a comment; it describes and documents the code for the programmer(s).
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Above is a class definition for the `Program` class.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Everything that follows between the pair of braces describes that class.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The curly brackets demarcate the boundaries of a code block.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] In this first instance, they are marking the start and end of the `Program` class.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] This declares the class member method where the program begins execution.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The .NET runtime calls the `Main` method.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike in Java, the `Main` method does not need the `public` keyword, which tells the compiler that the method can be called from anywhere by any class.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Writing `static void Main(string[] args)` is equivalent to writing `private static void Main(string[] args)`.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The static keyword makes the method accessible without an instance of `Program`.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Each console application's `Main` entry point must be declared `static` otherwise the program would require an instance of `Program`, but any instance would require a program.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] To avoid that irresolvable circular dependency, C# compilers processing console applications (like that above) report an error if there is no `static Main` method.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The `void` keyword declares that `Main` has no return value.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] `Console` is a static class in the `System` namespace.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] It provides an interface to the standard input/output, and error streams for console applications.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The program calls the `Console` method `WriteLine`, which displays on the console a line with the argument, the string `"Hello, World!"`.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] With .NET 2.0 and C# 2.0, the community got more flexible collections than those in .NET 1.x.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] In the absence of generics, developers had to use collections such as ArrayList to store elements as objects of unspecified kind, which incurred performance overhead when boxing/unboxing/type-checking the contained items.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Generics introduced a massive new feature in .NET that allowed developers to create type-safe data structures.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] This shift is particularly important in the context of converting legacy systems, where updating to generics can significantly enhance performance and maintainability by replacing outdated data structures with more efficient, type-safe alternatives.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] In August 2001, Microsoft, Hewlett-Packard and Intel co-sponsored the submission of specifications for C# as well as the Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) to the standards organization Ecma International.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] In December 2001, ECMA released ECMA-334 *C# Language Specification*.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] C# became an ISO/IEC standard in 2003 (ISO/IEC 23270:2003 - *Information technology — Programming languages — C#*).
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] ECMA had previously adopted equivalent specifications as the 2nd edition of C#, in December 2002.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] In June 2005, ECMA approved edition 3 of the C# specification, and updated ECMA-334.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Additions included partial classes, anonymous methods, nullable types, and generics (somewhat similar to C++ templates).
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] In July 2005, ECMA submitted to ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22, via the latter's Fast-Track process, the standards and related TRs.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The C# language definition and the CLI are standardized under ISO/IEC and Ecma standards that provide reasonable and non-discriminatory licensing protection from patent claims.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft initially agreed not to sue open-source developers for violating patents in non-profit projects for the part of the framework that is covered by the Open Specification Promise.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft has also agreed not to enforce patents relating to Novell products against Novell's paying customers with the exception of a list of products that do not explicitly mention C#, .NET or Novell's implementation of .NET (The Mono Project).
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] However, Novell maintained that Mono does not infringe any Microsoft patents.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft also made a specific agreement not to enforce patent rights related to the Moonlight browser plugin, which depends on Mono, provided it is obtained through Novell.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] A decade later, Microsoft began developing free, open-source, and cross-platform tooling for C#, namely Visual Studio Code, .NET Core, and Roslyn.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Mono joined Microsoft as a project of Xamarin, a Microsoft subsidiary.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft has developed open-source reference C# compilers and tools.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The first compiler, Roslyn, compiles into intermediate language (IL), and the second one, RyuJIT, is a JIT (just-in-time) compiler, which is dynamic and does on-the-fly optimization and compiles the IL into native code for the front-end of the CPU.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] RyuJIT is open source and written in C++.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Roslyn is entirely written in managed code (C#), has been opened up and functionality surfaced as APIs.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] It is thus enabling developers to create refactoring and diagnostics tools.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] Two branches of official implementation are .NET Framework (closed-source, Windows-only) and .NET Core (open-source, cross-platform); they eventually converged into one open-source implementation: .NET 5.0.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] At .NET Framework 4.6, a new JIT compiler replaced the former.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The Unity game engine uses C# as its primary scripting language.
[src:monogame/c-sharp-programming-language] The Godot game engine has implemented an optional C# module due to a donation of $24,000 from Microsoft.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Within computing, **cross-platform software** (also called **multi-platform software**, **platform-agnostic software**, or **platform-independent software**) is computer software that is designed to work in several computing platforms.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] For example, a cross-platform application may run on Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform software may run on many platforms, or as few as two.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Some frameworks for cross-platform development are Codename One, ArkUI-X, Kivy, Qt, GTK, Flutter, NativeScript, Xamarin, Apache Cordova, Ionic, and React Native.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] A hardware platform can refer to an instruction set architecture.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] For example: ARM or the x86 architecture.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] These machines can run different operating systems.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Smartphones and tablets generally run ARM architecture, these often run Android or iOS and other mobile operating systems.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] A software platform can be either an operating system (OS) or programming environment, though more commonly it is a combination of both.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] An exception is Java, which uses an OS-independent virtual machine (VM) to execute Java bytecode.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] The Java language is typically compiled to run on a VM that is part of the Java platform.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] The Java virtual machine (Java VM, JVM) is a CPU implemented in software, which runs all Java code.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] This enables the same code to run on all systems that implement a JVM.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Java software can be executed by a hardware-based Java processor.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] This is used mostly in embedded systems.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Java code running in the JVM has access to OS-related services, like disk input/output (I/O) and network access, if the appropriate privileges are granted.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] The JVM makes the system calls on behalf of the Java application.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] This lets users to decide the appropriate protection level, depending on an access-control list (ACL).
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] For example, disk and network access is usually enabled for desktop applications, but not for browser-based applets.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] The Java Native Interface (JNI) can also be used to access OS-specific functions, with a loss of portability.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Currently, Java Standard Edition software can run on Microsoft Windows, macOS, several Unix-like OSs, and several real-time operating systems for embedded devices.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] For mobile applications, browser plugins are used for Windows and Mac based devices, and Android has built-in support for Java.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] There are also subsets of Java, such as Java Card or Java Platform, Micro Edition, designed for resource-constrained devices.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] For software to be considered cross-platform, it must function on more than one computer architecture or OS.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Developing such software can be a time-consuming task because different OSs have different application programming interfaces (API).
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Software written for one OS may not automatically work on all architectures that OS supports.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Just because software is written in a popular programming language such as C or C++, it does not mean it will run on all OSs that support that language—or even on different versions of the same OS.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Web applications are typically described as cross-platform because, ideally, they are accessible from any web browser: the browser is the platform.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Web applications generally employ a client–server model, but vary widely in complexity and functionality.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] It can be hard to reconcile the desire for features with the need for compatibility.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Basic web applications perform all or most processing from a stateless server, and pass the result to the client web browser.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] All user interaction with the application consists of simple exchanges of data requests and server responses.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] This type of application was the norm in the early phases of World Wide Web application development.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Such applications follow a simple transaction model, identical to that of serving static web pages.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Today, they are still relatively common, especially where cross-platform compatibility and simplicity are deemed more critical than advanced functionality.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Prominent examples of advanced web applications include the Web interface to Gmail and Google Maps.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Such applications routinely depend on additional features found only in the more recent versions of popular web browsers.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] These features include Ajax, JavaScript, Dynamic HTML, SVG, and other components of rich web applications.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Because of the competing interests of compatibility and functionality, numerous design strategies have emerged.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Many software systems use a layered architecture where platform-dependent code is restricted to the upper- and lowermost layers.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Graceful degradation attempts to provide the same or similar functionality to all users and platforms, while diminishing that functionality to a least common denominator for more limited client browsers.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] For example, a user attempting to use a limited-feature browser to access Gmail may notice that Gmail switches to basic mode, with reduced functionality but still of use.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Some software is maintained in distinct codebases for different (hardware and OS) platforms, with equivalent functionality.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] This requires more effort to maintain the code, but can be worthwhile where the amount of platform-specific code is high.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] This strategy relies on having one codebase that may be compiled to multiple platform-specific formats.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] One technique is conditional compilation.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] With this technique, code that is common to all platforms is not repeated.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Blocks of code that are only relevant to certain platforms are made conditional, so that they are only interpreted or compiled when needed.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Another technique is separation of functionality, which disables functionality not supported by browsers or OSs, while still delivering a complete application to the user.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] (See also: Separation of concerns.) This technique is used in web development where interpreted code (as in scripting languages) can query the platform it is running on to execute different blocks conditionally.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Third-party libraries attempt to simplify cross-platform capability by hiding the complexities of client differentiation behind a single, unified API, at the expense of vendor lock-in.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Responsive web design (RWD) is a Web design approach aimed at crafting the visual layout of sites to provide an optimal viewing experience—easy reading and navigation with a minimum of resizing, panning, and scrolling—across a wide range of devices, from mobile phones to desktop computer monitors.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Little or no platform-specific code is used with this technique.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform applications need much more integration testing.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Some web browsers prohibit installation of different versions on the same machine.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] There are several approaches used to target multiple platforms, but all of them result in software that requires substantial manual effort for testing and maintenance.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Techniques such as full virtualization are sometimes used as a workaround for this problem.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Tools such as the Page Object Model allow cross-platform tests to be scripted so that one test case covers multiple versions of an app.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] If different versions have similar user interfaces, all can be tested with one test case.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Web applications are becoming increasingly popular but many computer users still use traditional application software which does not rely on a client/web-server architecture.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] The distinction between traditional and web applications is not always clear.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Features, installation methods and architectures for web and traditional applications overlap and blur the distinction.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Nevertheless, this simplifying distinction is a common and useful generalization.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Traditional application software has been distributed as binary files, especially executable files.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Executables only support the platform they were built for—which means that a single cross-platform executable could be very bloated with code that never executes on a particular platform.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Instead, generally there is a selection of executables, each built for one platform.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] For software that is distributed as a binary executable, such as that written in C or C++, there must be a software build for each platform, using a toolset that translates—transcompiles—a single codebase into multiple binary executables.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] For example, Firefox, an open-source web browser, is available on Windows, macOS (both PowerPC and x86 through what Apple Inc. calls a Universal binary), Linux, and BSD on multiple computer architectures.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] The four platforms (in this case, Windows, macOS, Linux, and BSD) are separate executable distributions, although they come largely from the same source code.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] In rare cases, executable code built for several platforms is combined into a single executable file called a fat binary.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] The use of different toolsets may not be enough to build a working executables for different platforms.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] In this case, programmers must *port* the source code to the new platform.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] For example, an application such as Firefox, which already runs on Windows on the x86 family, can be modified and re-built to run on Linux on the x86 (and potentially other architectures) as well.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] The multiple versions of the code may be stored as separate codebases, or merged into one codebase.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] An alternative to porting is *cross-platform virtualization*, where applications compiled for one platform can run on another without modification of the source code or binaries.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] As an example, Apple's Rosetta, which is built into Intel-based Macintosh computers, runs applications compiled for the previous generation of Macs that used PowerPC CPUs.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Another example is IBM PowerVM Lx86, which allows Linux/x86 applications to run unmodified on the Linux/Power OS.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] A script can be considered to be cross-platform if its interpreter is available on multiple platforms and the script only uses the facilities built into the language.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] For example, a script written in Python for a Unix-like system will likely run with little or no modification on Windows, because Python also runs on Windows; indeed there are many implementations (e.g.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] The same goes for many of the open-source scripting languages.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Unlike binary executable files, the same script can be used on all computers that have software to interpret the script.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] This is because the script is generally stored in plain text in a text file.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] There may be some trivial issues, such as the representation of a new line character.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform or multi-platform is a term that can also apply to video games released on a range of video game consoles.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Examples of cross-platform games include: *Miner 2049er*, *Tomb Raider: Legend*, *FIFA series*, *NHL series* and *Minecraft*.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Each has been released across a variety of gaming platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, personal computers, and mobile devices.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Some platforms are harder to write for than others, requiring more time to develop the video game to the same standard.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] To offset this, a video game may be released on a few platforms first, then later on others.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Typically, this happens when a new gaming system is released, because video game developers need to acquaint themselves with its hardware and software.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Some games may not be cross-platform because of licensing agreements between developers and video game console manufacturers that limit development to one particular console.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] As an example, Disney could create a game with the intention of release on the latest Nintendo and Sony game consoles.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Should Disney license the game with Sony first, it may be required to release the game solely on Sony's console for a short time or indefinitely.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Several developers have implemented ways to play games online while using different platforms.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Psyonix, Epic Games, Microsoft, and Valve all possess technology that allows Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 gamers to play with PC gamers, leaving the decision of which platform to use to consumers.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] The first game to allow this level of interactivity between PC and console games (Dreamcast with specially produced keyboard and mouse) was *Quake 3*.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Games that feature cross-platform online play include *Rocket League*, *Final Fantasy XIV*, *Street Fighter V*, *Killer Instinct*, *Paragon* and *Fable Fortune,* and *Minecraft* with its Better Together update on Windows 10, VR editions, Pocket Edition and Xbox One.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform programming is the practice of deliberately writing software to work on more than one platform.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] There are different ways to write a cross-platform application.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] One approach is to create multiple versions of the same software in different *source trees*—in other words, the Microsoft Windows version of an application might have one set of source code files and the Macintosh version another, while a FOSS *nix system might have a third.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] While this is straightforward, compared to developing for only one platform it can cost much more to pay a larger team or release products more slowly.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] It can also result in more bugs to be tracked and fixed.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Another approach is to use software that hides the differences between the platforms.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] This abstraction layer insulates the application from the platform.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Such applications are *platform agnostic*.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Applications that run on the JVM are built this way.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Some applications mix various methods of cross-platform programming to create the final application.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] An example is the Firefox web browser, which uses abstraction to build some of the lower-level components, with separate source subtrees for implementing platform-specific features (like the GUI), and the implementation of more than one scripting language to ease software portability.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Firefox implements XUL, CSS and JavaScript for extending the browser, in addition to classic Netscape-style browser plugins.
[src:monogame/cross-platform-software] Much of the browser itself is written in XUL, CSS, and JavaScript.
[src:monogame/game-engine] A **game engine** is a software framework primarily designed for video game development, which may include specialized software libraries and packages, such as level editors.
[src:monogame/game-engine] The term "engine" is a direct analogue of "software engine", having it employed across sectors of the software industry.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Furthermore, *game engine* may also refer to the integrated development environment as an interface behind the given framework, typically a suite of visual development tools and features for developing video games.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Game developers can use game engines to create and publish video games across platforms, such as desktops, mobile devices, video game consoles, and other types of computers.
[src:monogame/game-engine] The core functionalities commonly covered by a game engine are a 2D or 3D renderer, physics engine, audio engine, scripting, animation, artificial intelligence, networking, streaming, memory management, threads, localization support, scene graph, and cinematics.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Game engine developers often economize game development through reuse or adaptation of abstractions built into game engines for production of various games, or through porting of videogames from a single to other target platforms.
[src:monogame/game-engine] In many cases, game engines provide a suite of visual development tools in addition to reusable software components.
[src:monogame/game-engine] These tools are generally provided in an integrated development environment to enable simplified, rapid development of games in a data-driven manner.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Game-engine developers often attempt to preempt implementer needs by developing robust software suites, which include many elements a game developer may need to build a game.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Most game-engine suites provide facilities that ease development, such as graphics, sound, physics and artificial intelligence (AI) functions.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Like other types of middleware, game engines usually provide platform abstraction, allowing the same game to run on various platforms (including game consoles and personal computers) with few, if any, changes made to the game source code.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Often, programmers design game engines with a component-based architecture that allows specific systems in the engine to be replaced or extended with more specialized (and often more expensive) game-middleware components.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Some game engines comprise a series of loosely-connected game middleware components that can be selectively combined to create a custom engine, instead of the more common approach of extending or customizing a flexible integrated product.
[src:monogame/game-engine] However achieved, extensibility remains a high priority for game engines due to the wide variety of uses for which they are applied.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Despite the specificity of the name "game engine", end users often re-purpose game engines for other kinds of interactive applications with real-time graphical requirements—such as marketing demos, architectural visualizations, training simulations, and modeling environments.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Some game engines only provide real-time 3D rendering capabilities instead of the wide range of functionality needed by games.
[src:monogame/game-engine] These engines rely upon the game developer to implement the rest of this functionality or to assemble it from other game-middleware components.
[src:monogame/game-engine] These types of engines are generally referred to as a "graphics engine", "rendering engine", or "3D engine" instead of the all-encompassing term "game engine".
[src:monogame/game-engine] This terminology is inconsistently used, as many full-featured 3D game engines are simply referred to as "3D engines".
[src:monogame/game-engine] Examples of graphics engines include: Crystal Space, Genesis3D, Irrlicht, OGRE, RealmForge, Truevision3D, and Vision Engine.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Modern game- or graphics-engines generally provide a scene graph—an object-oriented representation of the 3D game-world which often simplifies game design and can be used for more efficient rendering of vast virtual worlds.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Most game engines or graphics engines use a Graphics API, which eases communication with the GPU.
[src:monogame/game-engine] But older games did not have hardware acceleration or GPUs and had to build their own software renderer.
[src:monogame/game-engine] As technology ages, the components of an engine may become obsolete or insufficient for the requirements of a given project.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Since the complexity of programming an entirely new engine may result in unwanted delays (or necessitate that a project restart from the beginning), an engine-development team may elect to update their existing engine with newer functionality or components.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Game engines are not limited to use in the video game field, and have found uses in other scientific fields.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Part of this is due to game engines being optimized for consumer-grade computing equipment rather than high-performance computing, allowing researchers to develop programs for their use on lower cost machines.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Game engines also simplify many of the computing operations needed for scientific software, including graphics, networking, and interactivity, reducing the need to develop these features themselves.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Before game engines, games were typically written as singular entities: a game for the Atari 2600, for example, had to be designed from the bottom up to make optimal use of the display hardware—this core display routine is now called the kernel by developers of games for older systems.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Other platforms had more leeway, but even when display was not a concern, memory constraints usually sabotaged attempts to create the data-heavy design that an engine needs.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Even on more accommodating platforms, very little could be reused between games.
[src:monogame/game-engine] The rapid advance of arcade hardware—which was the leading edge of the market at the time—meant that most of the code would have to be thrown out afterwards anyway, as later generations of games would use completely different game designs that took advantage of extra resources.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Thus, most game designs through the 1980s were designed through a hard-coded rule set with a small number of levels and graphics data.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Since the golden age of arcade video games, it became common for video game companies to develop in-house game engines for use with first-party software.
[src:monogame/game-engine] A notable example of an in-house game engine on home consoles in the mid-1980s was the smooth side-scrolling engine developed by Shigeru Miyamoto's team at Nintendo for the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES).
[src:monogame/game-engine] The engine they had developed for the side-scrolling racing game *Excitebike* (1984) was later employed for the scrolling platformer *Super Mario Bros.* (1985).
[src:monogame/game-engine] This allowed Mario to smoothly accelerate from a walk to a run, rather than move at a constant speed like in earlier platformers.
[src:monogame/game-engine] While third-party game engines were not common until the rise of 3D computer graphics in the 1990s, several 2D game creation systems were produced in the 1980s for independent video game development.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Klik & Play (1994) is another legacy offering that is still available.
[src:monogame/game-engine] The term *game engine* emerged in the mid-1990s, particularly with the rise of 3D games like first-person shooters, which often featured a dedicated first-person shooter engine.
[src:monogame/game-engine] For instance, Epic Games, founded by Tim Sweeney, debuted its Unreal Engine in 1998.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Later games, such as id Software's *Quake III Arena* and Epic Games' *Unreal* (1998), were designed with this approach in mind, with the engine and content developed separately.
[src:monogame/game-engine] At the very least, reusable engines make developing game sequels faster and easier, which is a valuable advantage in the competitive video game industry.
[src:monogame/game-engine] While a strong rivalry existed between Epic Games and id Software around 2000, Epic Game's Unreal Engine has since become far more popular than id Tech 4 and its successor, id Tech 5.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Modern game engines are some of the most complex applications written, often featuring dozens of finely-tuned systems interacting to ensure a precisely-controlled user experience.
[src:monogame/game-engine] The continued evolution of game engines has created a strong separation between rendering, scripting, artwork, and level design.
[src:monogame/game-engine] As such, it is now common, for example, for a typical game development team to have several times as many artists as actual programmers.
[src:monogame/game-engine] While third-party game engines are predominantly used in the development of first-person shooter games, they are also being used across other genres.
[src:monogame/game-engine] For example, Gamebryo is used in *The Elder Scrolls III: Morrowind* and *Dark Age of Camelot*, whereas Unreal Engine 2 is used in *Lineage II*.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Game engines are also used for games originally developed for home consoles, with RenderWare for the *Grand Theft Auto* and *Burnout* franchises as an example.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Due to modern multi-core systems and growing demands in realism, exploiting threads has become more important.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Separate threads of execution within a game engine manage intensive operations, including rendering, asset streaming, audio playback, and physics simulation.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Racing games have typically been at the forefront of threading with the physics engine running in a separate thread long before other core subsystems were moved, partly because rendering and related tasks need updating at only 30–60 Hz.
[src:monogame/game-engine] For example, on PlayStation 3, physics ran in *Need For Speed* at 100 Hz, versus *Forza Motorsport 2* at 360 Hz.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Although the term was first used in the 1990s, few earlier systems in 1980s are considered as game engines, such as Sierra's Adventure Game Interpreter (AGI) and SCI systems, LucasArts' SCUMM system and Incentive Software's Freescape engine (in 1986).
[src:monogame/game-engine] Unlike most modern game engines, these game engines were never used in any third-party products (except for the SCUMM system, which was licensed to and used by Humongous Entertainment).
[src:monogame/game-engine] As game engine technology matures and becomes more user friendly, the application of game engines has widened in scope.
[src:monogame/game-engine] They are now used for serious games: visualization, training, medical, and military simulation applications, with the CryEngine being one example.
[src:monogame/game-engine] To improve accessibility, new hardware platforms are also now targeted by game engines, including mobile phones (e.g.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Additionally, more game engines are being built upon higher-level languages, such as Java, C# and .NET (e.g., TorqueX, and Visual3D.NET), Python (Panda3D), or Lua Script (Leadwerks).
[src:monogame/game-engine] As most 3D-rich games are now mostly limited by the power of a graphics card, the potential slowdown due to translation overheads of higher-level languages becomes negligible, while productivity gains offered by these languages serve the game engine developers' benefit.
[src:monogame/game-engine] These recent trends are being propelled by companies such as Microsoft to support indie game development.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Microsoft developed XNA as the primary Software Development Kit (SDK) for all video games released on Xbox and their related products.
[src:monogame/game-engine] This includes the Xbox Live Indie Games channel designed specifically for smaller developers who do not have the extensive resources necessary to box games for sale on retail shelves.
[src:monogame/game-engine] It is becoming easier and cheaper than ever to develop game engines for platforms that support managed frameworks.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Producers of game engines decide how they allow users to use their products.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Just as gaming is an industry, so are the engines they are built off.
[src:monogame/game-engine] The major game engines come at varying prices, whether it be in the form of subscription fees or license payments.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Unity and Unreal Engine are currently the two most popular choices for game developers.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Although the differences among the different game engines blur as they build their own tools on top of them, different game developers may be too used to a system to change, or attracted by the huge benefits of such engines regardless of pay-walls.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Free and open-source engines such as Godot, have seen a rise in popularity, particularly following the 2023 Unity pricing controversy which drove game developers and studios to seek engines with a permissive license.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Applied more broadly, game engines themselves can be described as middleware.
[src:monogame/game-engine] In video games, however, *middleware* is often used to refer to subsystems of functionality within a game engine.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Some game middleware does only one thing, yet does it more convincingly or more efficiently than general purpose middleware.
[src:monogame/game-engine] The four most-widely used middleware packages that provide subsystems of functionality include RAD Game Tools' Bink, Firelight FMOD, Havok, and Scaleform GFx.
[src:monogame/game-engine] RAD Game Tools develops Bink for basic video rendering, along with Miles audio, and Granny 3D rendering.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Firelight FMOD is a low cost robust audio library and toolset.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Havok provides a robust physics simulation system, along with a suite of animation and behavior applications.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Scaleform provides GFx for high performance Flash UI and high-quality video playback, and an Input Method Editor (IME) addon for in-game Asian chat support.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Other middleware is used for performance optimization—for example Simplygon helps to optimize and generate level of detail meshes, and Umbra adds occlusion culling optimizations to 3D graphics.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Some middleware contains full source code, or is provided an API reference for a compiled binary library.
[src:monogame/game-engine] Some middleware programs can be licensed either way, usually for a higher fee for full source code.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] In many respects*, XNA* can be thought of as a .NET analog to Microsoft's better known game development system, DirectX, but it is aimed at developers primarily interested in writing lightweight games.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] XNA is the basic platform for Xbox Live Indie Games.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] As of January 2013, XNA is no longer being developed, and it is not compatible with Windows Runtime (the API for developing Metro-style apps), which was introduced with Windows 8.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] Microsoft XNA Framework is based on the native implementation of .NET Compact Framework 2.0 for Xbox 360 development and .NET Framework 2.0 on Windows.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] It includes an extensive set of class libraries, specific to game development, to promote maximum code reuse across target platforms.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] The framework runs on a version of the Common Language Runtime that is optimized for gaming to provide a managed execution environment.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] The runtime is available for Windows XP, Windows Vista, Windows 7, Windows Phone and Xbox 360.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] Since XNA games are written for the runtime, they can run on any platform that supports the XNA Framework with minimal or no modification.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] Games that run on the framework can technically be written in any .NET-compliant language, but only C# in XNA Game Studio Express IDE and all versions of Visual Studio 2008 and 2010 (as of XNA 4.0) are officially supported.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] Support for Visual Basic .NET was added in 2011.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] The XNA Framework integrates with a number of tools, such as the Cross-platform Audio Creation Tool (XACT), to aid in content creation.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] The XNA Framework provides support for both 2D and 3D game creation and allows use of the Xbox 360 controllers and vibrations.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] XNA framework games that target the Xbox 360 platform could only be distributed by members of the Microsoft XNA Creator's Club/App Hub, which carried a $99/year subscription fee.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] Desktop applications can be distributed free of charge under Microsoft's current licensing.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] XNA Build is a set of game asset pipeline management tools, which help by defining, maintaining, debugging, and optimizing the *game asset pipeline* of individual game development efforts.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] A *game asset pipeline* describes the process by which game content, such as textures and 3D models, are modified to a form suitable for use by the gaming engine.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] XNA Build helps identify the pipeline dependencies, and also provides API access to enable further processing of the dependency data.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] The dependency data can be analyzed to help reduce the size of a game by finding content that is not actually used.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] For example, XNA Build analysis revealed that 40% of the textures that shipped with *MechCommander 2* were unused and could have been omitted.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] XNA Game Studio is a programming environment for development of games.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] Five revisions have been released so far, but as of 2015, no new versions will be developed.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] XNA Game Studio Express was the first version released on August 30, 2006, and was intended for students, hobbyists, and independent game developers.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] Express provides basic "starter kits" for rapid development of specific genres of games, such as platform games, real-time strategy, and first-person shooters.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] Developers could create Windows games for free with the XNA Framework, but to run their games on the Xbox 360 they will have to pay an annual fee of US$99 (or a four-month fee of US$49) for admission to the Microsoft XNA Creator's Club.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] With an update, XNA developers could compile Xbox 360 binaries and share them with other Microsoft XNA Creator's Club members.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] XNA Game Studio 2.0 was released on December 13, 2007.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] XNA Game Studio 2.0 features the ability to be used with all versions of Visual Studio 2005 (including the free Visual C# 2005 Express Edition), a networking API using Xbox Live on both Windows and Xbox 360 and better device handling.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] XNA Game Studio 3.0 (for Visual Studio 2008 or the free Visual C# 2008 Express Edition) allows production of games targeting the Zune platform and adds Xbox Live community support.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] It was released on October 30, 2008, and supported C# 3.0, LINQ and most versions of Visual Studio 2008.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] XNA Game Studio 4.0 was released on September 16, 2010.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] XNA "Game Studio 4.0 Refresh" was released on 6 October 2011, and added support for Windows Phone 7.5 (Mango), and Visual Basic.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] The XNA Framework Content Pipeline is a set of tools that allows Visual Studio and XNA Studio to act "as the key design point around organizing and consuming 3D content".
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] Formerly known as XNA Game Studio Professional, XDK Extensions is an add-on to XNA Game Studio and requires the Microsoft Xbox 360 Development Kit.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] Both are only available for licensed Xbox developers.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] The extensions include additional managed APIs for achievements, leaderboards, and other features reserved for licensed game titles.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] Titles developed using XDK Extensions include winners of Microsoft's Dream.Build.Play competition among others.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] The most heavily publicized of these was *The Dishwasher: Dead Samurai*.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] The Microsoft XNA Framework 2.0 EULA specifically prohibits the distribution of commercial networked games that connect to Xbox Live and/or Games for Windows Live in the absence of a specific agreement signed by both the developer and Microsoft.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] This means that XNA Game Studio can still be used to develop commercial games and other programs for the Windows platform, although Microsoft's networking support code for Xbox/Windows Live cannot be used.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] Self-developed network code can still be used inside the developer's XNA project.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] Games created using XNA Game Studio may be distributed via the Windows Phone marketplace, and formerly via Xbox Live Indie Games.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] The software may also be used to create commercial games which target Windows.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] Dream Build Play was an annual and global $75,000 Microsoft contest promoting Microsoft XNA and eventually Xbox Live Indie Games, although it predated it.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] The contest was first announced in 2006 and first opened in January 2007.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] Many winners are notable developers in the Indie game community.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] Xbox 360 games written in XNA Game Studio could be submitted to the App Hub, for which premium membership was required (about US$99/year).
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] All games submitted to the App Hub were subjected to peer review by other creators.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] If the game passed review then it would be listed on Xbox Live Marketplace.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] Creators could set a price of 80, 240 or 400 points for their game.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] The creator is paid 70% of the total revenue from their game sales as a baseline.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] Microsoft originally planned to take an additional percentage of revenue if they provided additional marketing for a game, but this policy was rescinded in March 2009, leaving the flat rate intact regardless of promotion.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] Microsoft also distributed a free year premium App Hub subscription for educational establishments through their DreamSpark program and MSDNAA.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] These accounts allowed students to develop games for the Xbox 360, but developers still needed a premium Xbox Live account to submit their game to the marketplace.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] A project called Mono.XNA was formed to port XNA to the open source and cross-platform Mono framework.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] From the codebase of Mono.XNA and SilverSprite, a new project called MonoGame was formed to port XNA to several mobile devices.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] As of version 3.0.1 (released March 3, 2013), support is stable for iOS, Android including OUYA, macOS, Linux and Metro for Windows 8, Windows RT and Windows Phone 8, as well as PlayStation Mobile in 2D.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] PlayStation Mobile 3D and Raspberry Pi development are currently in progress.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] FNA is a full-featured open source reimplementation of XNA forked from MonoGame.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] The goal of FNA is to preserve the XNA game library by reimplementing XNA itself.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] An open source project called Grommet contains a limited port for embedded devices using the .NET Micro Framework.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] A project called ANX is available which implements its own version of XNA using the SharpDX stack; support for Linux, macOS and the PlayStation Vita is in progress as well.
[src:monogame/microsoft-xna] Using ANX, developers are able to write games using code that is very similar to XNA, while still being considered a Metro application in Windows 8.
[src:monogame/monogame] MonoGame is a derivative of XNA Touch (September 2009) started by José Antonio Farias and Silver Sprite by Bill Reiss.
[src:monogame/monogame] The first official release of MonoGame was version 2.0 with a downloadable version 0.7 that was available from CodePlex.
[src:monogame/monogame] These early versions only supported 2D sprite-based games.
[src:monogame/monogame] The last official 2D-only version was released as 2.5.1 in June 2012.
[src:monogame/monogame] Since mid-2013, the framework has begun to be extended beyond XNA4 with the addition of new features like RenderTarget3D, support for multiple GameWindows, and a new cross-platform command line content building tool.
[src:monogame/monogame] As of 2025, MonoGame continues to be used by indie developers for cross-platform 2D and 3D games, including recent releases on Steam and Xbox.
[src:monogame/monogame] MonoGame attempts to fully implement the XNA 4 API.
[src:monogame/monogame] It accomplishes this across Microsoft platforms using SharpDX and DirectX.
[src:monogame/monogame] When targeting non-Microsoft platforms, platform-specific capabilities are utilized by way of the OpenTK library.
[src:monogame/monogame] When targeting OS X, iOS, and/or Android, the Xamarin platform runtime is necessary.
[src:monogame/monogame] This runtime provides a tuned OpenTK implementation that allows the MonoGame team to focus on the core graphics tuning of the platform.
[src:monogame/monogame] The graphics capabilities of MonoGame come from either OpenGL, OpenGL ES, or DirectX.
[src:monogame/monogame] Since MonoGame version 3, OpenGL 2 has been the focus for capabilities.
[src:monogame/monogame] The earlier releases of MonoGame (2.5) used OpenGL 1.x for graphics rendering.
[src:monogame/monogame] Utilizing OpenGL 2 allowed MonoGame to support shaders, enabling more advanced rendering capabilities on the platform.
[src:monogame/monogame] Content management and distribution continue to follow the XNA 4 ContentManager model.
[src:monogame/monogame] The MonoGame team has created a new content building capability that can integrate with Microsoft Visual Studio to deliver the same content building capabilities to Windows 8 Desktop that Windows 7 users used in Microsoft XNA.
[src:monogame/net] The **.NET** platform (pronounced as "*dot net"*; formerly named **.NET Core**) is a free and open-source, managed computer software framework for Windows, Linux, and macOS operating systems.
[src:monogame/net] It is a cross-platform successor to the .NET Framework.
[src:monogame/net] The project is mainly developed by Microsoft employees by way of the .NET Foundation and is today released under an MIT License.
[src:monogame/net] New versions of the .NET platform are released annually, typically in November.
[src:monogame/net] The most recent version of .NET is .NET 10, released in November 2025, which is a long-term support (LTS) version, and is scheduled to receive updates until November 2028.
[src:monogame/net] In the late 1990s, Microsoft began developing a managed code runtime and programming language (C#) which it billed together as part of the ".NET platform", with the core runtime and software libraries comprising the .NET Framework.
[src:monogame/net] Soon after the announcement of the C# language at the Professional Developers Conference in 2000 and previews of its software became available, Microsoft began a standardization effort through ECMA for what it dubbed the Common Language Infrastructure.
[src:monogame/net] The company continued development and support of its own implementation as proprietary, closed source software in the meantime.
[src:monogame/net] Miguel de Icaza describes .NET Core as a "redesigned version of .NET that is based on the simplified version of the class libraries", and Microsoft's Immo Landwerth explained that .NET Core would be "the foundation of all future .NET platforms".
[src:monogame/net] At the time of the announcement, the initial release of the .NET Core project had been seeded with a subset of the libraries' source code and coincided with the relicensing of Microsoft's existing .NET reference source away from the restrictions of the Ms-RSL.
[src:monogame/net] Landwerth acknowledged the disadvantages of the formerly selected shared license, explaining that it made codename Rotor "a non-starter" as a community-developed open source project because it did not meet the criteria of an Open Source Initiative (OSI) approved license.
[src:monogame/net] .NET Core 1.0 was released on June 27, 2016, along with Microsoft Visual Studio 2015 Update 3, which enables .NET Core development. .NET Core 1.0.4 and .NET Core 1.1.1 were released along with .NET Core Tools 1.0 and Visual Studio 2017 on March 7, 2017.
[src:monogame/net] .NET Core 2.0 was released on August 14, 2017, along with Visual Studio 2017 15.3, ASP.NET Core 2.0, and Entity Framework Core 2.0. .NET Core 2.1 was released on May 30, 2018.
[src:monogame/net] NET Core 2.2 was released on December 4, 2018.
[src:monogame/net] .NET Core 3 was released on September 23, 2019.
[src:monogame/net] NET Core 3 adds support for Windows desktop application development and significant performance improvements throughout the base library.
[src:monogame/net] In November 2020, Microsoft released .NET 5.0.
[src:monogame/net] The "Core" branding was abandoned and version 4.0 was skipped to avoid conflation with .NET Framework, of which the latest releases had all used 4.x versioning for all significant (non-bugfix) releases since 2010.
[src:monogame/net] .NET Core Runtime roughly uses semantic versioning, the *major.minor.patch* format.
[src:monogame/net] Major versions are incremented with "significant changes", API-breaking changes, or with the major version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:monogame/net] Minor versions are incremented with the addition of API features, dependencies, or with the minor version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:monogame/net] Patch versions are given for bug fixes, new platform support, or other changes not included above.
[src:monogame/net] As of 2019, runtime versions are backwards-compatible within the same major version number.
[src:monogame/net] For example, .NET Core 2.2 is able to run programs built for .NET Core 2.1.
[src:monogame/net] Runtime versions in the same minor version.
[src:monogame/net] This appears to have relaxed since .NET 5.
[src:monogame/net] A "roll-forward" behavior allows any .NET program to be run on any newer version given the correct settings.
[src:monogame/net] The SDK does not use semantic versioning.
[src:monogame/net] As of 2019, it supports targeting *every* runtime version prior to its maximum supported version.
[src:monogame/net] As of 2020, this extends down to .NET Framework runtimes as well, though downloading an additional "targeting pack" from NuGet may be necessary.
[src:monogame/net] The major and minor versions of an SDK always matches the major and minor versions of the runtime it contains or is aligned for.
[src:monogame/net] Alpine Linux, which primarily supports and uses musl libc, is supported since .NET Core 2.1.
[src:monogame/net] Windows Arm64 is natively supported since .NET 5.
[src:monogame/net] Previously, .NET on ARM meant applications compiled for the x86 architecture and run through the ARM emulation layer.
[src:monogame/net] Linux .NET runs on Power ISA to some extent since .NET 7, officially no support is claimed by Microsoft but .NET does contain code for Power ISA compatibility for Linux systems and is able to be compiled for Power ISA systems specifically 64 bit Little Endian variant.
[src:monogame/net] .NET fully supports C# and F# (and C++/CLI as of 3.1; only enabled on Windows) and supports Visual Basic .NET (for version 15.5 in .NET Core 5.0.100-preview.4, and some old versions supported in old .NET Core).
[src:monogame/net] VB.NET compiles and runs on .NET, but as of .NET Core 3.1, the separate Visual Basic Runtime is not implemented.
[src:monogame/net] Microsoft initially announced that .NET Core 3 would include the Visual Basic Runtime, but after two years the timeline for such support was updated to .NET 5.
[src:monogame/net] .NET supports the following cross-platform scenarios: ASP.NET Core web apps, command-line/console apps, libraries and Universal Windows Platform apps.
[src:monogame/net] Prior to .NET Core 3.0, it did not implement Windows Forms or Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF), which render the standard GUI for desktop software on Windows.
[src:monogame/net] However, from .NET Core 3 on, it started implementing them along with Universal Windows Platform (UWP).
[src:monogame/net] It was also possible to write cross-platform graphical applications using .NET with the GTK# language-binding for the GTK widget toolkit, but this binding has not been maintained for many years.
[src:monogame/net] Unlike .NET Framework, which is serviced using Windows Update, .NET used to rely on its package manager to receive updates.
[src:monogame/net] Since December 2020, however, .NET updates started being delivered via Windows Update as well.
[src:monogame/net] NuGet serves as the primary distribution mechanism for libraries and tools in the .NET ecosystem, including third-party components that extend core functionality.
[src:monogame/net] Among these are ADO.NET-compatible data providers, which offer database connectivity for systems beyond the default SQL Server support.
[src:monogame/net] These providers enable direct access to databases such as Oracle, MySQL, PostgreSQL, and others, and are commonly used in applications that require cross-platform data access, integration with ORM technologies, or support for specific database features.
[src:monogame/net] The two main components of .NET are CoreCLR and CoreFX, which are comparable to the Common Language Runtime (CLR) and the Framework Class Library (FCL) of the .NET Framework's Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) implementation.
[src:monogame/net] As an implementation of CLI's Standard Libraries, CoreFX shares a subset of .NET Framework APIs, however, it also comes with its own APIs that are not part of the .NET Framework.
[src:monogame/net] A variant of the .NET library is used for UWP.
[src:monogame/net] The .NET command-line interface offers an execution entry point for operating systems and provides developer services like compilation and package management.
[src:monogame/net] The official community mascot of .NET is the .NET Bot (stylized as "dotnet bot" or "dotnet-bot").
[src:monogame/net] The dotnet bot served as the placeholder developer for the initial check-in of the .NET source code when it was open-sourced.
[src:monogame/net] It has since been used as the official mascot.
